HEADWORD: Succuba
<hw>Suc"cu*ba</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Succubae</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL., fr. L.
<ets>succubare</ets> to lie under; <ets>sub</ets> under +
<ets>cubare</ets> to lie down; cf. L. <ets>succuba</ets>,
<ets>succubo</ets>, one who lies under another.]</ety> <def>A female
demon or fiend. See <er>Succubus</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though seeming in shape a woman natural⟦br⟧
Was a fiend of the kind that <qex>succubae</qex> some call.</q>
<rj><qau>Mir. for Mag.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Succubine</ent>⟦br⟧
